</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Myriad benign tumors may be found in the liver; they can be classified according to their cell of origin into tumors of hepatocellular, cholangiocellular, or mesenchymal origin. Common benign hepatic tumors may pose a diagnostic dilemma when they manifest with atypical imaging features. Less frequently encountered benign hepatic tumors such as inflammatory pseudotumor or biliary cystadenoma demonstrate less specific imaging features; however, awareness of their findings is useful in narrowing differential diagnostic considerations. In addition, certain iatrogenically induced abnormalities of the liver may be confused with more ominous findings such as infection or neoplasia. However, knowledge of their common imaging appearances, in addition to the clinical history, is critical in correctly diagnosing and characterizing iatrogenic abnormalities of the liver. Familiarity with both expected and unexpected imaging appearances of common benign hepatic tumors, less commonly encountered benign hepatic tumors, and iatrogenic abnormalities potentially masquerading as hepatic tumors allows the radiologist to achieve an informed differential diagnosis.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.291085099">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.291085099">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g01x.jpeg" height="1572" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1.</b>  Hepatic adenomas in a patient with type IA glycogen storage disease (von Gierke disease). Axial unenhanced computed tomographic (CT) image shows multiple relatively hyperattenuating lesions (arrowheads), findings consistent with adenomas. Note the abnormally low attenuation of the surrounding liver parenchyma secondary to diffuse fatty infiltration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g02a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1442" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  Typical MR imaging characteristics of hepatic adenoma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted image shows a lesion (arrow) that is slightly hyperintense relative to normal liver parenchyma. <b>(b)</b> Arterial phase contrast-enhanced image shows brisk, slightly heterogeneous enhancement of the lesion (arrow). Note the absence of a central scar.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g02b.jpeg" height="1465" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  Typical MR imaging characteristics of hepatic adenoma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted image shows a lesion (arrow) that is slightly hyperintense relative to normal liver parenchyma. <b>(b)</b> Arterial phase contrast-enhanced image shows brisk, slightly heterogeneous enhancement of the lesion (arrow). Note the absence of a central scar.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g03x.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3.</b>  Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained during the late arterial phase shows an enhancing adenoma (arrow) in the left hepatic lobe. The adenoma has ruptured, and surrounding hemoperitoneum is visible (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03c04x.jpeg" height="960" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4.</b>  FNH. Color Doppler image shows prominent central vasculature (arrow) in a hepatic mass (arrowheads) with an otherwise nonspecific appearance.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g05a.jpeg" height="1594" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  Typical MR imaging characteristics of FNH. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows a relatively hypointense lesion (arrow) with a hypointense central scar. <b>(b)</b> On a T2-weighted image, the lesion (arrow) is relatively hyperintense. The central scar is hyperintense. <b>(c)</b> Arterial phase T1-weighted image shows brisk enhancement of the lesion (arrow). The central scar (arrowhead) is hypointense. <b>(d)</b> On a delayed phase T1-weighted image, the lesion (arrow) is minimally hyperintense and the central scar (arrowhead) is relatively hyperintense.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g05b.jpeg" height="1594" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  Typical MR imaging characteristics of FNH. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows a relatively hypointense lesion (arrow) with a hypointense central scar. <b>(b)</b> On a T2-weighted image, the lesion (arrow) is relatively hyperintense. The central scar is hyperintense. <b>(c)</b> Arterial phase T1-weighted image shows brisk enhancement of the lesion (arrow). The central scar (arrowhead) is hypointense. <b>(d)</b> On a delayed phase T1-weighted image, the lesion (arrow) is minimally hyperintense and the central scar (arrowhead) is relatively hyperintense.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g05c.jpeg" height="1594" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5c.</b>  Typical MR imaging characteristics of FNH. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows a relatively hypointense lesion (arrow) with a hypointense central scar. <b>(b)</b> On a T2-weighted image, the lesion (arrow) is relatively hyperintense. The central scar is hyperintense. <b>(c)</b> Arterial phase T1-weighted image shows brisk enhancement of the lesion (arrow). The central scar (arrowhead) is hypointense. <b>(d)</b> On a delayed phase T1-weighted image, the lesion (arrow) is minimally hyperintense and the central scar (arrowhead) is relatively hyperintense.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F5C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g05d.jpeg" height="1594" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5d.</b>  Typical MR imaging characteristics of FNH. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows a relatively hypointense lesion (arrow) with a hypointense central scar. <b>(b)</b> On a T2-weighted image, the lesion (arrow) is relatively hyperintense. The central scar is hyperintense. <b>(c)</b> Arterial phase T1-weighted image shows brisk enhancement of the lesion (arrow). The central scar (arrowhead) is hypointense. <b>(d)</b> On a delayed phase T1-weighted image, the lesion (arrow) is minimally hyperintense and the central scar (arrowhead) is relatively hyperintense.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F5D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g06x.jpeg" height="986" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6.</b>  Delayed phase T1-weighted MR image, obtained 2 hours after administration of gadobenate dimeglumine, shows a hepatic lesion (arrow) that is relatively hyperintense, a finding highly specific for FNH.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g07x.jpeg" height="1196" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7.</b>  Multiple dysplastic nodules in a patient with cirrhosis. Arterial phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows multiple enhancing liver nodules (arrowheads), a nonspecific finding that may be seen with dysplastic hepatocellular nodules.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g08x.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8.</b>  NRH in a patient with an autoimmune disorder. T2-weighted MR image shows large hypointense nodules (arrows) with marked low signal intensity, which is due to iron accumulation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g09a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1080" aria-labelledby="F9A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9a.</b>  Sequelae of infection or hemorrhage in hepatic cysts. <b>(a)</b> US image of a thick-walled hepatic cyst (arrow) shows internal debris. <b>(b)</b> US image of another hepatic cyst (arrow) shows somewhat thickened internal septa (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F9A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g09b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1080" aria-labelledby="F9B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9b.</b>  Sequelae of infection or hemorrhage in hepatic cysts. <b>(a)</b> US image of a thick-walled hepatic cyst (arrow) shows internal debris. <b>(b)</b> US image of another hepatic cyst (arrow) shows somewhat thickened internal septa (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F9B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g10x.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10.</b>  Biliary hamartomas in an otherwise healthy patient. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows numerous hypoattenuating lesions (arrowheads) in the liver.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g11a.jpeg" height="1042" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Peribiliary cysts. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows tubular hypoattenuating areas (arrows) along the portal tracts of the liver, findings consistent with peribiliary cysts. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding axial T2-weighted MR image shows tubular areas of high signal intensity (arrows) along the portal tracts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g11b.jpeg" height="972" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Peribiliary cysts. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows tubular hypoattenuating areas (arrows) along the portal tracts of the liver, findings consistent with peribiliary cysts. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding axial T2-weighted MR image shows tubular areas of high signal intensity (arrows) along the portal tracts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g12x.jpeg" height="1144" width="1584" aria-labelledby="F12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12.</b>  Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous hypoattenuating biliary cystadenoma (arrow), which has the unusual feature of growth into and along adjacent bile ducts (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g13x.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13.</b>  Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a complex heterogeneous biliary cystadenoma (arrow) with an enhancing nodular area (arrowhead). These findings are virtually indistinguishable from those of a biliary cystadenocarcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g14x.jpeg" height="1282" width="1709" aria-labelledby="F14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14.</b>  Caroli disease. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows segmental saccular dilatation of intrahepatic bile ducts (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g15x.jpeg" height="1269" width="1692" aria-labelledby="F15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15.</b>  Hepatic hemangiomas in a patient with Osler-Weber-Rendu syndrome. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows numerous enhancing lesions (arrows), which represent hepatic hemangiomas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g16x.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16.</b>  Focal fatty infiltration. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a focal region of low attenuation in the liver (arrow), a finding consistent with focal geographic fatty infiltration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g17x.jpeg" height="1294" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17.</b>  Hepatic angiomyolipoma. US image shows a well-circumscribed lesion (arrows) with a focal relatively hyperechoic component (arrowhead), which represents macroscopic fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g18a.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F18A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18a.</b>  Hepatic angiomyolipoma. <b>(a)</b> T1-weighted MR image shows a relatively hypointense lesion (arrow) with a peripheral area of relative high signal intensity (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> On a T1-weighted MR image obtained with fat suppression, there is a significant decrease in the signal intensity of the hyperintense component (arrowhead) of the angiomyolipoma (arrow). The decreased signal intensity is consistent with macroscopic fat. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image shows intense enhancement of the angiomyolipoma (arrow). Owing to the use of fat suppression, the component of macroscopic fat remains hypointense (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F18A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g18b.jpeg" height="1287" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F18B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18b.</b>  Hepatic angiomyolipoma. <b>(a)</b> T1-weighted MR image shows a relatively hypointense lesion (arrow) with a peripheral area of relative high signal intensity (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> On a T1-weighted MR image obtained with fat suppression, there is a significant decrease in the signal intensity of the hyperintense component (arrowhead) of the angiomyolipoma (arrow). The decreased signal intensity is consistent with macroscopic fat. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image shows intense enhancement of the angiomyolipoma (arrow). Owing to the use of fat suppression, the component of macroscopic fat remains hypointense (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F18B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g18c.jpeg" height="1268" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F18C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18c.</b>  Hepatic angiomyolipoma. <b>(a)</b> T1-weighted MR image shows a relatively hypointense lesion (arrow) with a peripheral area of relative high signal intensity (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> On a T1-weighted MR image obtained with fat suppression, there is a significant decrease in the signal intensity of the hyperintense component (arrowhead) of the angiomyolipoma (arrow). The decreased signal intensity is consistent with macroscopic fat. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image shows intense enhancement of the angiomyolipoma (arrow). Owing to the use of fat suppression, the component of macroscopic fat remains hypointense (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F18C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g19a.jpeg" height="1063" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F19A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19a.</b>  Peliosis hepatis. <b>(a)</b> Arterial phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows brisk early enhancement of a lesion (arrow) in the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> Portal venous phase CT image shows mild washout in the lesion (arrow), with lower attenuation than on the arterial phase image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F19A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g19b.jpeg" height="1063" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F19B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19b.</b>  Peliosis hepatis. <b>(a)</b> Arterial phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows brisk early enhancement of a lesion (arrow) in the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> Portal venous phase CT image shows mild washout in the lesion (arrow), with lower attenuation than on the arterial phase image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F19B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g20x.jpeg" height="1386" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20.</b>  Paraganglioma with nonspecific imaging characteristics. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-circumscribed lesion in the liver (arrow). The lesion has brisk enhancement with a central area of relatively low attenuation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g21a.jpeg" height="1349" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F21A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21a.</b>  Imaging appearances of inflammatory pseudotumor of the liver. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large, predominantly hypoattenuating lesion (arrow) with central low attenuation. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of another lesion (arrow) shows both central and marked peripheral enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F21A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g21b.jpeg" height="1349" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F21B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21b.</b>  Imaging appearances of inflammatory pseudotumor of the liver. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large, predominantly hypoattenuating lesion (arrow) with central low attenuation. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of another lesion (arrow) shows both central and marked peripheral enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F21B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g22a.jpeg" height="1352" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F22A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22a.</b>  Variable appearances of liver lesions after chemoembolization. <b>(a)</b> CT image shows a gas-containing collection (arrow) that mimics an abscess. Significant tumor lysis may release nitrogen and form a gas-containing collection; however, the lack of fluid in the area is atypical for a focal infection. Arrowhead = area of relatively high attenuation. <b>(b)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image of a patient who recently underwent chemoembolization shows areas of high attenuation (arrows), which represent the numerous lesions that were treated. <b>(c)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image, obtained in a patient who underwent chemoembolization further back in time, shows residual areas of relatively high attenuation (arrowheads) within relatively hypoattenuating liver lesions. Without knowledge of the patient’s history, the high-attenuation areas may be mistaken for the psammomatous calcifications associated with certain adenocarcinoma metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F22A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g22b.jpeg" height="1352" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F22B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22b.</b>  Variable appearances of liver lesions after chemoembolization. <b>(a)</b> CT image shows a gas-containing collection (arrow) that mimics an abscess. Significant tumor lysis may release nitrogen and form a gas-containing collection; however, the lack of fluid in the area is atypical for a focal infection. Arrowhead = area of relatively high attenuation. <b>(b)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image of a patient who recently underwent chemoembolization shows areas of high attenuation (arrows), which represent the numerous lesions that were treated. <b>(c)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image, obtained in a patient who underwent chemoembolization further back in time, shows residual areas of relatively high attenuation (arrowheads) within relatively hypoattenuating liver lesions. Without knowledge of the patient’s history, the high-attenuation areas may be mistaken for the psammomatous calcifications associated with certain adenocarcinoma metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F22B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g22c.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F22C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22c.</b>  Variable appearances of liver lesions after chemoembolization. <b>(a)</b> CT image shows a gas-containing collection (arrow) that mimics an abscess. Significant tumor lysis may release nitrogen and form a gas-containing collection; however, the lack of fluid in the area is atypical for a focal infection. Arrowhead = area of relatively high attenuation. <b>(b)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image of a patient who recently underwent chemoembolization shows areas of high attenuation (arrows), which represent the numerous lesions that were treated. <b>(c)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image, obtained in a patient who underwent chemoembolization further back in time, shows residual areas of relatively high attenuation (arrowheads) within relatively hypoattenuating liver lesions. Without knowledge of the patient’s history, the high-attenuation areas may be mistaken for the psammomatous calcifications associated with certain adenocarcinoma metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F22C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g23a.jpeg" height="1352" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F23A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23a.</b>  Pseudolesions related to surgical defects. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image shows omental packing within a surgical defect (arrow). Note that the surgical margins extend to the edge of the liver. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows packing with oxidized regenerated cellulose (arrow). The air-containing area within the liver defect may be mistaken for an abscess; knowledge of the surgical history is critical in these cases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F23A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g23b.jpeg" height="1245" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F23B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23b.</b>  Pseudolesions related to surgical defects. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image shows omental packing within a surgical defect (arrow). Note that the surgical margins extend to the edge of the liver. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows packing with oxidized regenerated cellulose (arrow). The air-containing area within the liver defect may be mistaken for an abscess; knowledge of the surgical history is critical in these cases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F23B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g24x.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24.</b>  Hematoma due to a percutaneous needle biopsy. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a significant masslike hematoma (arrows) in the liver. If one is unaware of the clinical history, this finding may be mistaken for an intrahepatic mass lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F25" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g25x.jpeg" height="1162" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 25.</b>  Liver abnormality in a patient with a history of radiofrequency ablation of a hepatoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a focal, well-circumscribed area of low attenuation (arrow). If one is unaware of the clinical history, this finding may be mistaken for a focal mass lesion or an intrahepatic collection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g26x.jpeg" height="1215" width="1620" aria-labelledby="F26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26.</b>  Retractor injuries in a patient who underwent a Whipple procedure. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows heterogeneous enhancement within several areas of the liver (arrows). These findings are consistent with retractor injuries related to the surgery and are typically seen in portions of the left hepatic lobe. Knowledge of the patient’s history and preoperative images are helpful in definitively making this diagnosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F27A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g27a.jpeg" height="1352" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F27A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 27a.</b>  Radiation injury to the liver. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image shows a geographic area of low attenuation (arrowheads) involving most of the left hepatic lobe and portions of the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> Portal venous phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows relatively low attenuation in the area of radiation injury (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Delayed phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows relatively high attenuation in the area of radiation injury (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F27A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F27B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g2b.jpeg" height="1352" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F27B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 27b.</b>  Radiation injury to the liver. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image shows a geographic area of low attenuation (arrowheads) involving most of the left hepatic lobe and portions of the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> Portal venous phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows relatively low attenuation in the area of radiation injury (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Delayed phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows relatively high attenuation in the area of radiation injury (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F27B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F27C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03g27c.jpeg" height="1296" width="1728" aria-labelledby="F27C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 27c.</b>  Radiation injury to the liver. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image shows a geographic area of low attenuation (arrowheads) involving most of the left hepatic lobe and portions of the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> Portal venous phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows relatively low attenuation in the area of radiation injury (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Delayed phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows relatively high attenuation in the area of radiation injury (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085099&amp;id=F27C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T1" class="table"><figcaption><b>Classic MR Imaging Characteristics of Common Benign Hepatic Lesions</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085099/asset/images/g09ja03t01x.jpeg" height="950" width="1800" aria-labelledby="T1" loading="lazy" /><div class="notes"><div role="doc-footnote"><b>*</b>Relative to that of adjacent normal hepatic parenchyma.</div></div></figure></div><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Brancatelli</span><span class="named-content" data-type="art